1. PCA Analysis

1)Conduct a principal component analysis for the training dataset. Illustrate the percent that each eigenvalue contributes to the total sample variance. How many principal components will be enough to explain at least 90% of the total sample variance in the training data?

Below, principal components are presented with respect to their representation of percentage variance. Based on results, principal components up to 7th component explain 92.794% of the variance in the dataset.

2. Top 7 PCA and Linear Discriminant Analysis

2. (15 points) Suppose that you decide to use a principal components in part (1) to summarize the original training cata. Get the scores of these ki components for each observation, and then use these scores to conduct the linear discriminant analysis (LDA). What is the misclassification error rate based on the training data set? Apply the obtained linear discriminant rule to the test data set, what is the error rate?

Selecting top 7 principle component results presented. Linear Discriminant Analysis model is developed based on these principal components.

Misclassification rate of 0.39 is achieved with PCA based data in the training set. In the test set, misclassification rate is resulted as 0.939, which is a high rate of misclassification. It can be expressed that further analysis is required to make a successful prediction.

train.pca.df.7 <- data.frame(train.pca$x)

train.pca.df.7$y <- train.df$y

#Fit the model
model <- lda(y~., data = train.pca.df.7)
#Make predictions
predictions <- model %>% predict(train.pca.df.7)

3. Quadratic Discriminant Analysis

3. (10 points) Repeat the work in part (2) and do the quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA). Does QDA give lower testing error rate?

Results for QDA show higher misclassification error in test set, when compared to training results. While training results for misclassification rate is 0.08, test set result is 0.90. The model can not be adequate to conduct successful predictions in this phase.

4. Original Data Based LDA & QDA

4. (15 points) For the original training data set, conduct linear discriminant analysis and quadratic discriminant analysis, and get the error rates. Apply these rules to the test data and get the error rates. Summarize these error rates with those from parts (2) and (3) in a table and comment on the results.

Results show that the most successful training results are in QDA model, applied to original data. The least successful one is LDA model, applied with PCA version of the data. When test sets are observed, QDA model applied to original data provides the most successful results. While, LDA model applied to PCA version of the data result with least successful results. It can be interpreted that the dataset is more suitable when the original version is used to train a model. Also, QDA model provides superior results than LDA. The most successful quantitative test outcome is by QDA with original data, where misclassification rate is 0.53.

5. Eliminating classes which are hard to distinguish

5. (15 points) What classes do you think are most difficult to distinguish from others? If these classes are removed, how does the test error rates for LDA and QDA change? Compare with results from part (4).

In this part, 8 different models are presented, with their misclassification scores for training and testing sets. Results show that when classes which are hardly distinguished (5,7,10) removed, both original data based and pca based models present more successful results. Original data based LDA model’s misclassification score drops as low as 0.39, which is the most successful score among all models. QDA model follows it with 0.46. Class removal has been conducted based on LDA model’s test set results and 5,7 and 10 are found to be suitable for this action. Other experiments were also conducted though lowest score achieved has been 0.39, so 5,7,10 are removed for the final presentation purpose.

6. Clustering

6. (20 points) To simplify it, select observations from classes 1, 3, 6 and 10 and conduct clustering analysis on these observations. Try the hierarchical clustering methods, K-means method and model-based clustering method. Comment on the performance of these methods.

In clustering analysis, since 4 classes of data are introduced, 4 is selected as the target number of clusters for the sake of comparison. Also, 4 is determined to be optimum number of clusters based on with in sum of squares analysis and elbow method.

When Model outcomes are measured with adjusted rand index, it is observed that kmeans has the highest result with 0.40, followed by hiearchical as 0.13 and model based clustering as 0.22. It can be expressed that kmeans is the most effective model as we compare real class labels and assigned class labels.

Model performances also can be interpreted in several perspectives. First, in terms of computation and time efficiency, k-means and hierarchical clustering have faster processing, while model based clustering is the most costly methodology. Also, model based clustering is computationally the most costly methodology. Other than that, models can be interpreted on the basis of assumptions. K-means and hierarchical clustering are unsupervised methods and do not assume any information regarding the dataset. While, model based clustering has distinct assumption of multivariate normality of the data. This is an important limitation for model based clustering and due to this reason, analysis is conducted in a careful manner. In terms of explainability of models to non-technical individuals, hierarchical and k-means are more easily explainable while due to limitations, model based clustering is more challenging to interpret.’

7. [10 points) What is the final conclusion based on the previous methods?

As the result, LDA has been the most successful model where classes 5,7,10 are removed. Removal of classes generated a positive impact in the results. PCA based analyses did not provide useful outcomes. Some reasons on this might be due to nature of the dataset. In the original data where all classes are present, QDA has been more successful than LDA. While, PCA application when classes are removed does not provide useful results, just like the initial PCA model. It can be concluded that the most succesful application has been done with LDA where certain classes are removed.

Training errors are significantly lower, when compared to testing. This shows a sign of overfitting in all models. LDA and QDA can be mentioned to have tendency for overfit in the scope of this analysis.

Clustering also provided significant insights. K-means has been the most successful result, where 0.42 is achieved as the adjusted rand index. In terms of performance, k-means showed it can be the most trusted model. Model based clustering and hierarchical clustering did not provide adjusted rand index as high as k-means.

As the future work, advanced models can be implemented and tested to reach better misclassification rates.
